<font color="#FF0000">TO JED</font><br>
<tt>Sat Dec 27  8:22:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Regarding your last paragraph: I served in an infantry unit in the Americal Division. When I arrived in the field my company - C company 1/52 198th LIB had  black Staff Sergeants serving as Platoon Sergeants for each of our *four* platoons. The previous Commanding Officer, a captain, was a black man. Granted, these are not upper echelon positions, nonetheless, they indicate that there were many black soldiers in command positions. <br><br>
Also, there were many many black soldiers who had SUPPORT MOS's, and who were stationed in support areas. These types of jobs, for obvious reasons, were much desired by many who fought in combat units. <br><br>
If your first paragraph is an attempt to connect a predominate &quot;racist&quot; philosophy with an inordinate amount of blacks in the bush, I disagree. <br><br>
Any numbers which may be considered disproportionate, in my opinion, are more reflective of a society which enabled draft age men, from wealthier circumstances, to stay in school and avoid being drafted.<br><br>
If you want to look at numbers, then look at the numbers of poor whites who fought in Viewtnam. I am certain there were a disproportionate amount of them fighting also.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


